import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming tmdb is your DataFrame
# Convert 'release_date' column to datetime format
tmdb['release_date'] = pd.to_datetime(tmdb['release_date'])

# Plotting number of movies released each year
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
tmdb['release_date'].dt.year.value_counts().sort_index().plot(kind='bar')
plt.title('Number of Movies Released Each Year')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Number of Movies')
plt.show()

# Seasonality Analysis
# Extract month from release_date
tmdb['release_month'] = tmdb['release_date'].dt.month

# Group movies by release month and calculate average revenue
average_revenue_by_month = tmdb.groupby('release_month')['revenue'].mean()

# Plot average revenue by month
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(average_revenue_by_month.index, average_revenue_by_month.values, marker='o', linestyle='-')
plt.title('Average Revenue by Release Month')
plt.xlabel('Month')
plt.ylabel('Average Revenue')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
In [60]:
# Revenue and Budget Trends Over Years
# Group movies by release year and calculate average budget and revenue
average_budget_by_year = tmdb.groupby(tmdb['release_date'].dt.year)['budget'].mean()
average_revenue_by_year = tmdb.groupby(tmdb['release_date'].dt.year)['revenue'].mean()

# Plot average budget and revenue by year
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(average_budget_by_year.index, average_budget_by_year.values, marker='o', linestyle='-', label='Average Budget')
plt.plot(average_revenue_by_year.index, average_revenue_by_year.values, marker='o', linestyle='-', label='Average Revenue')
plt.title('Average Budget and Revenue Over Years')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Amount')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
